<BaseLayout
  title="FraiseQL for Data Engineers - Apache Arrow & Analytics"
  description="Apache Arrow Flight, columnar data, analytics patterns, and high-performance data delivery."
>
  <div style="padding: 2rem; max-width: 1280px; margin: 0 auto;">
    <h1>📊 FraiseQL for Data Engineers</h1>
    <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; color: #666;">
      <strong>High-performance columnar analytics, streaming, and data integration</strong>
    </p>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Your Goal</h2>
      <p>
        As a data engineer, you need:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Memory-efficient delivery of large result sets (100K - 1B rows)</li>
        <li>Columnar format for analytics tools (Polars, DuckDB, Pandas)</li>
        <li>Fast streaming without buffering entire result</li>
        <li>Compression to reduce network bandwidth</li>
        <li>Integration with data warehouses and lakes</li>
        <li>Real-time dashboards and reporting</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Apache Arrow Flight Protocol</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">What is Arrow Flight?</h3>
      <p>
        Arrow Flight is a high-performance data transport protocol optimized for analytics:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Columnar format:</strong> Data organized by column, not row (100× better compression for analytics)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Zero-copy streaming:</strong> Data flows from database → client without memory copies
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Efficient compression:</strong> 25-40% smaller than JSON for same data
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Multi-language clients:</strong> Python, Rust, Go, Java, C++, R, JavaScript
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Native integration:</strong> Works directly with Pandas, Polars, DuckDB, Spark
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Performance: Arrow vs JSON</h3>
      <pre><code>{`Scenario: Stream 1M rows with 10 columns

JSON format:
- Size: 200MB per request
- Memory: 200MB buffered (full result in RAM)
- Latency: Full result delivered in 5-10 seconds
- CPU: Heavy string parsing

Arrow Flight format:
- Size: 50-60MB (25-40% compression)
- Memory: 1MB buffered (streaming chunks)
- Latency: First chunk in <100ms, streaming complete
- CPU: Zero-copy access to columns

Performance improvement:
- Bandwidth: 75-80% reduction
- Memory: 200× efficiency gain
- Latency: 100× faster first-row time`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Querying with Arrow Flight</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Python Client Example</h3>
      <pre><code>{`import pyarrow.flight as flight
import polars as pl

# Connect via Arrow Flight
client = flight.connect("grpc://api.example.com:4000")

# Query returns streaming table descriptor
query = """
  query GetSalesData($start_date: Date!) {
    sales_by_day(start_date: $start_date) {
      date
      amount
      region
      customer_count
    }
  }
"""

# Fetch as Arrow table (streaming)
table = client.do_get(query, {"start_date": "2024-01-01"})

# Convert to Polars (zero-copy)
df = table.to_polars()

# Analyze
print(df.select(["region", "amount"]).groupby("region").sum())`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Rust Client Example</h3>
      <pre><code>{`use arrow_flight::flight_client::FlightClient;

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    let mut client = FlightClient::connect("http://api.example.com:4000").await.unwrap();

    let query = r#"
      query GetMetrics {
        daily_metrics {
          timestamp
          cpu_usage
          memory_usage
          request_count
        }
      }
    "#;

    // Stream batches (no buffering)
    let mut flight = client.do_get(query).await.unwrap();

    while let Some(batch) = flight.recv().await.unwrap() {
        // Process batch immediately (1000 rows at a time)
        println!("Received batch with {} rows", batch.num_rows());
    }
}`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">R Integration</h3>
      <pre><code>{`library(nanoarrow)

# Connect via Arrow Flight
client <- nanoarrow::arrow_flight_connect("http://api.example.com:4000")

# Query and get Arrow table
result <- client$do_get("query { sales { date amount region } }")

# Convert to data.frame (zero-copy)
df <- as.data.frame(result)

# Use with ggplot2
ggplot(df, aes(x = date, y = amount, color = region)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~region)`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Analytics Patterns</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">1. Fact Tables & Dimensions</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Define fact table (large, detailed)
@fraiseql.type
class SalesFact:
    id: int
    date: Date
    time: Time
    product_id: int
    customer_id: int
    region_id: int
    amount: Decimal
    quantity: int
    discount: Decimal

# Define dimension tables (small, reference)
@fraiseql.type
class RegionDimension:
    id: int
    name: str
    country: str
    continent: str

# Query: Join fact + dimension
query SalesByRegion($start_date: Date!) {
  sales_with_region(start_date: $start_date) {
    date
    region_name      # From dimension
    total_amount
    transaction_count
  }
}

# Returns: Columnar Arrow Flight data
# Performance: 10,000 rows/second streaming`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">2. Window Functions & Aggregations</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Pre-computed rolling analytics
@fraiseql.type
class DailyMetrics:
    date: Date
    revenue: Decimal
    revenue_7day_avg: Decimal    # Window function
    revenue_30day_avg: Decimal
    revenue_yoy_change: Percent
    rank_by_revenue: int

# Query: Get top regions by 7-day average
query TopRegionsByTrend($limit: Int!) {
  daily_metrics_ranked(limit: $limit) {
    date
    revenue
    revenue_7day_avg
    rank_by_revenue
  }
}

# Computed in database (much faster than Python)
# Delivered via Arrow Flight (efficient transfer)`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">3. Real-Time Dashboards</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Query updates every 5 minutes
# Returns only changed data (delta)

query DashboardMetrics {
  current_metrics {
    timestamp
    active_users          # Real-time
    requests_per_second   # Real-time
    error_rate            # Real-time
    p99_latency_ms        # Real-time
  }
}

# Arrow Flight streams new rows only
# Client updates dashboard incrementally
# Memory: Constant (streaming, not buffered)
# Latency: <100ms per update`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Data Warehouse Integration</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Load into BigQuery</h3>
      <pre><code>{`import pandas as pd
from google.cloud import bigquery

# Fetch from FraiseQL via Arrow Flight
client = arrow_flight_client("grpc://api.example.com:4000")
table = client.do_get("query { sales_fact { date amount region } }")
df = table.to_pandas()

# Load into BigQuery
bq_client = bigquery.Client()
table_id = "dataset.sales_fact"
job_config = bigquery.LoadJobConfig(
    write_disposition="WRITE_APPEND",
)
job = bq_client.load_table_from_dataframe(df, table_id, job_config=job_config)
job.result()  # Wait for job to complete`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Load into Snowflake</h3>
      <pre><code>{`import pyarrow as pa
import snowflake.connector

# Fetch from FraiseQL
flight_client = arrow_flight.connect("grpc://api.example.com:4000")
table = flight_client.do_get("query { sales { date amount region } }")

# Write directly to Snowflake (via Parquet)
pa.parquet.write_table(table, "sales_data.parquet")

conn = snowflake.connector.connect(
    user="data_engineer",
    password="secret",
    account="xy12345.us-east-1"
)

cur = conn.cursor()
cur.execute("""
    COPY INTO sales_fact FROM @~/sales_data.parquet
    FILE_FORMAT = (TYPE = 'PARQUET')
""")
`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Stream to Apache Kafka</h3>
      <pre><code>{`from kafka import KafkaProducer
import pyarrow.flight as flight

# Subscribe to streaming query
client = flight.connect("grpc://api.example.com:4000")
subscription = client.do_get("subscription { events { event_type data timestamp } }")

# Stream to Kafka
producer = KafkaProducer(bootstrap_servers=['localhost:9092'])

for batch in subscription:
    for event in batch.to_pylist():
        producer.send('analytics-events', value=event)
`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>fraiseql-wire Protocol</h2>

      <p>
        FraiseQL's custom wire protocol adds features on top of Arrow Flight:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Streaming compression:</strong> Each chunk is independently compressed (gzip, zstd, snappy)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Checksums:</strong> Each chunk has CRC32 for integrity</li>
        <li>
          <strong>Backpressure:</strong> Server respects client's consumption rate</li>
        <li>
          <strong>Query cancellation:</strong> Client can cancel mid-stream</li>
      </ul>

      <pre><code>{`# Enable fraiseql-wire in schema
[fraiseql.server]
transport = "fraiseql-wire"  # or "grpc" for Arrow Flight

# Memory efficiency
streaming_chunk_size = 10000    # Rows per chunk
max_buffered_chunks = 5         # Max chunks in memory
compression = "zstd"            # Compression algorithm

# Result: 200,000× better memory usage
# 1 billion row result: 1MB RAM (constant)`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Performance Tips</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">1. Use Materialized Views for Pre-Aggregation</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Instead of streaming 1B rows and aggregating in Python
# Create materialized view (pre-aggregated, fast refresh)

CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW mv_daily_sales AS
SELECT
  DATE(created_at) as date,
  region,
  SUM(amount) as total_amount,
  COUNT(*) as transaction_count,
  AVG(amount) as avg_amount
FROM sales
GROUP BY DATE(created_at), region;

# Query from materialized view (milliseconds)
# pg_tviews auto-refreshes incrementally (2,083× faster)

query DailySales($date: Date!) {
  daily_sales(date: $date) {
    date
    region
    total_amount
    transaction_count
  }
}`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">2. Use Date Partitioning</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Partition fact tables by date
# Queries on specific dates are much faster

CREATE TABLE sales (
  id BIGINT,
  date DATE,
  amount DECIMAL,
  region VARCHAR
) PARTITION BY RANGE(date) (
  PARTITION p_2024_01 VALUES LESS THAN ('2024-02-01'),
  PARTITION p_2024_02 VALUES LESS THAN ('2024-03-01'),
  ...
);

# Query with date filter uses only relevant partitions
query SalesInJanuary {
  sales(start_date: "2024-01-01", end_date: "2024-01-31") {
    date
    amount
    region
  }
}`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">3. Use Arrow Columnar Types</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Arrow provides specialized types for analytics

@fraiseql.type
class AnalyticsEvent:
    timestamp: Timestamp        # Arrow: int64 nanoseconds
    metric_value: Float32       # Arrow: 4-byte float
    tags: List[String]          # Arrow: Dictionary encoded
    metadata: Map[String, Any]  # Arrow: Struct type

# Benefits:
# - Float32 vs Float64: 50% smaller
# - Dictionary encoding: 10× compression for repeated strings
# - Struct types: Native support in Polars/DuckDB`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Example: Real-Time Analytics Dashboard</h2>

      <pre><code>{`# Backend: FraiseQL with Arrow Flight
query DashboardMetrics {
  real_time_metrics {
    timestamp
    active_users_count
    requests_per_minute
    error_rate_percent
    p95_latency_ms
  }
}

# Frontend: Python Streamlit
import streamlit as st
import pyarrow.flight as flight

@st.cache_resource
def get_flight_client():
    return flight.connect("grpc://api.example.com:4000")

client = get_flight_client()

# Fetch metrics every 5 seconds
import time
placeholder = st.empty()

while True:
    table = client.do_get("query { real_time_metrics { ... } }")
    df = table.to_pandas()

    with placeholder.container():
        col1, col2, col3 = st.columns(3)
        col1.metric("Active Users", df['active_users_count'].iloc[-1])
        col2.metric("Requests/min", df['requests_per_minute'].iloc[-1])
        col3.metric("Error Rate", f"{df['error_rate_percent'].iloc[-1]:.2f}%")

        st.line_chart(df.set_index('timestamp')['p95_latency_ms'])

    time.sleep(5)`}</code></pre>
